<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12021g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12021g">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12021g"> 21(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> miraculised</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> L&apos;abb&eacute; interrogea l&apos;&eacute;tranger. <br>Il n&apos;eut pas de peine &agrave; reconna&icirc;tre que cet individu appartenait &agrave; l&apos;une de ces bandes, plus ou moins honn&ecirc;tes, qui s&apos;introduisaient dans les monast&egrave;res, y recueillant, souvent, d&apos;abondantes aum&ocirc;nes, en racontant des histoires extraordinaires et &eacute;difiantes, dont ils pr&eacute;tendaient avoir &eacute;t&eacute; les h&eacute;ros. Ils se disaient, g&eacute;n&eacute;ralement, des miracul&eacute;s, affirmant avoir &eacute;t&eacute; gu&eacute;ris des maladies les plus graves et les plus cruelles, gr&acirc;ce &agrave; l&apos;intercession des saints particuli&egrave;rement honor&eacute;s dans le monast&egrave;re qu&apos;ils visitaient. Othbert raconta alors, avec une incroyable volubilit&eacute; et une mimique souvent grotesque, l&apos;aventure terrible dont il avait &eacute;t&eacute; le h&eacute;ros en 1021, dans la petite ville de Colebige sur le Wisper (aujourd&apos;hui K&ocirc;lbigh, duch&eacute; d&apos;Anhalt pr&egrave;s de Bernburg). <br><font color="green">[The abbott interrogated the stranger. <br>He had no trouble recognising that this individual belonged to one of the gangs, more or less honest, who came to the monasteries, often collected there lots of alms, telling extraordinary and edifying tales of which they pretended they had been the hero. They called themselves, generally, <mark>miraculised</mark>, affirming that they had healed from the most serious and most cruel illnesses, thanks to the intercession of saints that were particularly honoured in the monastery that they were visiting. Othbert told the story, with an unbelievable loquacity and an often grotesque mimicry, the terrible adventure of which he had been the hero in 1021, in the little city of Colebige on the Wisper (today K&ouml;lbigh, the duchy of Anhalt close to Bernburg)]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 40</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The miraculized: subjects of miracles.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c12004b" href="c12all.htm#c12004b">VI.C.12:004(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
